'''[[Cannabis]] in [[Kosovo]]''' is illegal for both medicinal or recreational purposes.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Legal status of cannabis in Kosovo - Cannaconnection.com|url=https://www.cannaconnection.com/blog/14798-legal-status-kosovo|access-date=2021-04-03|website=www.cannaconnection.com|date=13 August 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Kosovo : Is Cannabis Legal Yet?|url=https://iscannabislegalyet.com/kosovo|access-date=2021-04-03|website=iscannabislegalyet.com}}</ref> Penalties are defined by Article 269 of the Kosovo Criminal Code, last revised in January 2019. For first-time offenders, possession of illicit substances leads to either a one-year sentence or, more likely, a financial penalty of €250-300.<ref name="kosovotwopointzero">{{Cite web|date=2019-10-21|title=Kosovo should consider legalizing cannabis - Kosovo 2.0Kosovo 2.0|url=https://kosovotwopointzero.com/en/kosovo-should-consider-legalizing-cannabis/|access-date=2021-04-03|website=Kosovo 2.0}}</ref> A 2014 survey of 5500 reported that 10% of Kosovans knew someone who had used cannabis and 12.6% reported having easy access to cannabis.<ref name="kosovotwopointzero" />

==History==
The [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] ratified the [[Second International Opium Convention]] on 4 September 1929.<ref>{{Cite web|title=United Nations Treaty Collection|url=https://treaties.un.org/pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=VI-6-a&chapter=6&clang=_en|access-date=2021-04-03|website=treaties.un.org|language=EN}}</ref> The first law to sanction drug abuse was the Criminal Code of the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes passed on 27 January 1929 and which entered into force on 1 January 1930, which sets a prison sentence of up to 6 months for "serving" narcotic drugs in the section "Crimes against Public Health".<ref>{{cite book|title=Criminal Code of the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes|date=1929|publisher=Državna štamparija|location=Belgrade|pages=70–71}}</ref>

==Trafficking==
{{see also|Crime in Kosovo}}

Since the [[Kosovo War]], organised crime in Kosovo has engaged in the trafficking of drugs including marijuana alongside [[heroin]] and [[cocaine]]. Kosovo acts as a transit hub for traffic between [[Afghanistan]] and [[Italy]],<ref name=BalkanReportUN>{{cite web|title=CRIME AND ITS IMPACT ON THE BALKANS and affected countries|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Balkan_study.pdf|publisher=United Nations|access-date=23 February 2013|quote=For the purposes of this Report, the Balkans comprises the nine nations of the Stability Pact: Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, Moldova, Montenegro, Romania, and Serbia.}} (The report does not contain any data for Kosovo.) </ref> and from Albania to the rest of Europe.<ref>{{citation|title=Transnational Terrorism, Organized Crime and Peace-Building: Human Security in the Western Balkans|page=152|year=2010|isbn=9780230234628|publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|editor1-first=Christopher|editor1-last=Daase|editor2-first=Dimitrijevic |editor2-last=Vojin|editor3-first=Petrus |editor3-last=van Duyne|editor4-first=Wolfgang |editor4-last=Benedek|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Y8bAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> From 2001 to 2007, a total of 286.89&nbsp;kg of cannabis was seized by [[Kosovo Police]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iksweb.org/Photos/Publikimet/Images/Imazhi_%C3%A7on_pesh%C3%AB!/enIMIDZ_english.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203022545/http://www.iksweb.org/Photos/Publikimet/Images/Imazhi_%C3%A7on_pesh%C3%AB!/enIMIDZ_english.pdf |archive-date=3 December 2013| title=IMAGE MATTERS! Deconstructing Kosovo's Image Problem| page=24|date= November 2008}}</ref> [[Cannabis (drug)|Cannabis]] is cultivated in Kosovo, for domestic use primarily. The cultivation of cannabis is spread in most parts of the country's territory.<ref name=EMCDDA>{{cite web|title=Country overview: Kosovo (under UNSCR 1244/99)|url=http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/publications/country-overviews/xk|publisher=EMCDDA|access-date=23 February 2013|archive-date=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316190931/http://www.emcdda.europa.eu/publications/country-overviews/xk|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Nuhiu|first=Bajram|date=2019|others=Kosovo Police|title=Drug situation in Kosovo|url=https://leph2019edinburgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/ko_drug-situation.pdf|access-date=2021-04-03|website=LEPH 2019|publisher=LEPH}}</ref>

